## Minimum Shippable v1 (WF-1 through WF-5)

If the weekend runs short, the minimum shippable v1 is WF-1 through WF-5. WF-6 and WF-7 are stretch goals that validate full integration but are not required for products to begin adapter work.

The key question for Sunday night: can Sage, MSD, and NightCTO each write a product adapter against stable types? That requires WF-5 to be complete at minimum, because WF-5 is where `SurfaceRegistry`, `SurfaceConnection`, `SurfaceAdapter`, and the inbound/outbound adapter wiring are implemented and tested.

---

## Risk Flags

| Risk | Mitigation |
| --- | --- |
| Spec vocabulary drift causes wrong implementation | Treat `docs/specs/v1-*-spec.md` as the only source of truth; discard any planning doc that conflicts |
| WF-5 cross-package dependency is missed | WF-5 is core + surfaces; it requires `SurfaceRegistry` to implement `RelayInboundAdapter` + `RelayOutboundAdapter`; mark this explicitly in the workflow doc |
| Sessions `touch`/`expire` vs `resume`/`close` confusion | Use only the spec-defined method names; `resume` does not exist as a method — `touch()` handles it |
| `createSurfaceConnection` vs `SurfaceConnection` + `createSurfaceRegistry` confusion | Product code creates `SurfaceConnection` objects and registers them into `createSurfaceRegistry()` |
| NightCTO wants v1.1 features immediately | NightCTO can begin memory adapter stub work after v1 ships; memory spec is already IMPLEMENTATION_READY |
| WF-6/WF-7 cut for time | Acceptable — WF-1 through WF-5 is the minimum shippable v1; products can begin adapter work |
| Surface fanout semantics unclear in tests | Use normative rule: `surfaceId` present → `send()`, no `surfaceId` but `sessionId` → `fanout()` |

---

